column3: has never asked how they are or what's new in their lives..it's like they just don't exist to him.

column1: but that's not my problem or under my control.  what i can control is what happens now and that is to leave the state as soon as possible (but not before my lawyer files the name change i've been trying to have done for the past year)  i will never feel hopeless like i did the day i left
column2: instead i will find a new job
column3: in a new city and start a new and safe life away from him. my faith is bigger than anything that can come my way!

column1: this one is actually tough. i'm really torn between ariana grande's controversial single and camila cabello's latin-influenced hit. i'm gonna go with ""god is a woman"" because it was one of the most special pop records of 2018. ariana sounds heavenly on this song
column2: especially with those multi-layered background vocals towards the end that make it seem like there's a church choir singing with her. the video is very emblematic. also
column3: with the #metoo movement still going strong
column4: a song about the female perspective winning a grammy would send a positive message.

column2: i predict the award to go to the live version of camila cabello's ""havana"" because it was the biggest female song of 2018. this song was everywhere
column3: you could not escape it. it's got a (very) catchy hook and as soon as the beat drops
column4: you just know you're about to listen to  something good. i also feel like camila will walk away from that night with at least one grammy so if it isn't for the album
column5: it will more likely be for her biggest song to date.

column1: â€œthey must see americans as strange liberators. the vietnamese people proclaimed their own independence in 1954 -- in 1945 rather -- after a combined french and japanese occupation and before the communist revolution in china...even though they quoted the american declaration of independence in their own document of freedom
column2: we refused to recognize them. instead
column3: we decided to support france in its reconquest of her former colony. our government felt then that the vietnamese people were not ready for independence
column4: and we again fell victim to the deadly western arrogance that has poisoned the international atmosphere for so long... these are revolutionary times. all over the globe men are revolting against old systems of exploitation and oppression
column5: and out of the wounds of a frail world
column6: new systems of justice and equality are being born. the shirtless and barefoot people of the land are rising up as never before. ""the people who sat in darkness have seen a great light."" we in the west must support these revolutions.â€

column1: and be them. we live this fight everywhere - domestically and internationally - and everyday. for freedom. in solidarity. thank you dr. martin luther king. we fight through your legacy and alongside you. .

column1: i'm sharing this now because i imagine there are many more women who have had similar experiences.
last night i was at a beautiful lunar eclipse event. i have been making a point to go out more even than i did before since being in this dissociative state
column2: to let it know it has no power over my beingness. that i will show up numb and empty the same way i will show up full and rich with life.  however within this night i had a realization that because or being in a chronic freeze state
column3: i often do not have appropriate emotional responses to things

column1: i had an encounter with a strange man i had never met before
column2: he told me he was a donor/funder of the space i was in. he offered to give me a tour of places in the space i hadn't seen
column4: and so i went with him. he proceeded to take me into a room with a sauna and ask if i'd like to sauna and i said no
column5: he began to speak about things he had been through to gain sympathy i imagine
column6: and took his shirt off randomly. i was frozen. he was speaking to me of trauma and tantra and not having any knowledge of consent! after this i just stood there
column7: he continued to speak i stared blankly and then he removed his pants to ""show me his scars"" he did not ask if i was comfortable with him taking his clothes off in front of me. i didn't feel anything(because of dissociation etc) so my normal urgency to remove myself from the situation was not there
column8: and also i was not moving at all
column9: i imagine because i was afraid. several times he grabbed me by the shoulders and gave me hugs. he proceeded to put his clothes back on and two minutes later took his pants off again and put his arms out for a hug. i somehow snapped out of the trance and walked out. i was confused and told someone what had happened but heard myself immediately making excuses for his unwarranted behavior and jokes to ease the startled confusion. the truth is that this was not ok with me
column10: i was scared and frozen and being touched

column2: and tbh i don't feel much about it

column1: 187703;instagram;2019-01-21 17:31:15;FALSE;"!!!education education education!!! an educated populace will not stand for what is going on inside slaughterhouses.  an educated populace will not stand for discrimination or violence of any form.
to be an effective educator and communicator you must ask great questions while simultaneously challenging false beliefs
there is a fine line that must be walked.  you do not want to push people to hard
column2: but their identity has to be challenged and they need to have that 'a ha' moment on their own.

i started writing this piece a year ago in response to the monumental #metoo movement. .
sexual assault impacts us all in different ways; fear
this story is a thriller about a mother who after being attached and blackmailed must choose between protecting her son and unmasking a monster to protect future victims. .
i made it my mission to hire many strong women behind and and in front of the camera. and am beyond blessed by the incredible group of people that have come together to make this thing happen!

column1: 187833;instagram;2019-01-21 19:37:00;FALSE;"having being diagnosed with depression at 19.there are times when my depression has made me feel like i'm not doing anything right in my life and that the planet just whats me out in it. that's a tough thought to fight against
column2: because it feeds itself deep into the soul. but once you're convinced that you're worthless
column3: you stop doing anything worthwhile.then you suddenly become the person you already thought you were
column4: someone who naps for hours just to make the days go by faster
column5: and who looks for any excuse to avoid getting up or even turning on the light. or you start to eat uncontrollably and feel even more depressed when you look in the mirror.

column2: even if your depression is keeping you from being an active and putting you in ""zombie mode"". when i got help and began to start feeling like a human again
column3: i was able to reflect honestly on my achievements and the paths i have taken. and one of the things i'm proudest of
column4: which is something i cling to when the depressive tendencies tries to creep back
column5: is that i am more opened about my struggles
column6: ready to accept the feelings. i know how much it helps me to be reminded that i'm not alone. if i can do the same for others
column7: i know i'm doing something right.

column1: 187925;instagram;2019-01-21 22:04:27;FALSE;"""our lives begin to end the day we become silent about things that matter."" - martin luther king jr.
2018 was a rather first-of-its-sorts for me. it was the year i began to speak openly on taboo subjects that i've always felt strongly about internally. when i first started the blog
column2: i stayed away from writing about anything but food because it was the safe thing to do
column3: but a series of experiences last year changed that
column4: and me. it started with a visit to the martin luther king museum - the church where he preached
column5: the home where he was born
column6: the work that he did and the words that he spoke. amidst the outpour of tears that day came an awakening. and that feeling intensified during my visit to washington dc. words are magic - they move through time
column7: mold civilizations and shape the course of humanity. walking through the mlk memorial by the potomac
column8: all i could think of was
column9: 'i want to write some of these words'. but i am one tiny
column11: what could i possibly do? alone
column13: definitely) not much - i am a sand in the desert
column16: dust in the wind. but together - that's a different story... the #metoo movement comes to mind. someone very brave had to speak out to empower millions all over the world to say the words 'me too'. change happens when there is consensus. and for true consensus

column1: so now whenever i hear or see something that makes my insides squirm
column2: i make it a point to say something. ""nothing in the world is more dangerous than sincere ignorance and conscientious stupidity.""
as we honor the incomparable dr. king. and the next time your conscience twinges
column3: speak out. your words could strengthen another
column5: another - now that's the kind of infection we want spreading. what would you like to see changed in this world?
